## 2. The invariant — proven, with explicit scope

> **Theorem (BACL, Binade-Aligned Cancellation Lattice — proven 2026-05-18).**
>
> Let `a, b ∈ 𝔽⁺` (positive normal-range floats in any IEEE 754 binary format).
>
> **(BACL-S, sufficient direction):** If `floor_binade(a) ≥ floor_binade(b)`, then
>
> ```
>     a − b (real value) = j · ulp(b)  for some integer j ∈ ℤ.
> ```
>
> If additionally `|j| · ulp(b)` is exactly representable as a float (holds when `|j| ≤ 2^53 − 1` for float64, `|j| ≤ 2^24 − 1` for float32), then `round-to-nearest-even(a − b) = a − b` exactly in float arithmetic.
>
> **(BACL-N, sharpness):** The proviso `floor_binade(a) ≥ floor_binade(b)` is necessary in the sense that violating it admits non-integer multiples. Empirically, ~15–55% of pairs with `floor_binade(a) < floor_binade(b)` produce non-integer differences in ulp(b) units.

### Proof of BACL-S (5 lines, axiomatic)

> 1. By IEEE 754 binade spacing: every positive normal float `x` in binade `[2^k, 2^(k+1))` has the form `x = N · 2^(k−52)` for an integer `N ∈ [2^52, 2^53)` (float64; analogous for other formats). I.e., `x = N · ulp(x)`.
> 2. Let `k_a = floor_binade(a)`, `k_b = floor_binade(b)`. Hypothesis: `k_a ≥ k_b`.
> 3. `ulp(a) = 2^(k_a − 52) = 2^(k_a − k_b) · 2^(k_b − 52) = 2^(k_a − k_b) · ulp(b)`. Since `k_a ≥ k_b`, `ulp(a)` is a non-negative integer multiple of `ulp(b)`.
> 4. `a = N_a · ulp(a) = N_a · 2^(k_a − k_b) · ulp(b)`, integer multiple of `ulp(b)`. `b = N_b · ulp(b)`, trivially.
> 5. Therefore `a − b = (N_a · 2^(k_a − k_b) − N_b) · ulp(b)`, integer multiple of `ulp(b)`. **∎**

No Sterbenz invocation, no cancellation hypothesis, no rounding-mode dependence. The proof uses only binade structure and integer arithmetic.

